Product Version     25.10    Cadence Design Systems, Inc.
ecoAddRepeater(25.10)                                    ecoAddRepeater(25.10)

Name
       ecoAddRepeater - Adds either a single buffer or two inverters on a net

Syntax
       ecoAddRepeater

       [-help]

       {-net <netName> | -term <term1 term2>... }

       [-hinstGuide  <hinstName> | -spreadDist <distance> | -spreadCount <num-
       ber> ]

       [-name <instName> | -spreadDist <distance> | -spreadCount <number> ]

       [-spreadDist <distance> | -spreadCount <number> ]

       [-newNetName <netName> | -spreadDist <distance> | -spreadCount <number>
       ]

       [-loc {xLoc yLoc} | { xLoc yLoc inv_xLoc inv_yLoc} | -offLoadAtLoc {x1a
       y1a x1b y1b x2a y2a x2b y2b ....} | { xLoc yLoc  inv_xLoc  inv_yLoc}  |
       -offLoadSlack  <slack> | -spreadDist <distance> | -spreadCount <number>
       ]

       [-radius <mu>m | -logicalChangeOnly | -spreadDist <distance> | -spread-
       Count <number> ]

       [-offLoadAtLoc {x1a y1a x1b y1b x2a y2a x2b y2b ....}  |  {  xLoc  yLoc
       inv_xLoc  inv_yLoc}  | -offLoadSlack <slack> | -spreadDist <distance> |
       -spreadCount <number> ]

       [{[-loc {xLoc yLoc} | { xLoc yLoc inv_xLoc inv_yLoc}]

       [-relativeDistToSink <sinkWeight>]

       [-offLoadAtLoc {x1a y1a x1b y1b x2a y2a x2b y2b ....}  |  {  xLoc  yLoc
       inv_xLoc inv_yLoc}]} [ -radius <mu>m ] ]

       [-loc  {xLoc  yLoc}  | { xLoc yLoc inv_xLoc inv_yLoc} [-bufOrient {R0 |
       R90 | R180 | R270 | MX | MX90 | MY | MY90}]]

       [-net <netName> [-spreadDist <distance>]]

       [-spreadPrefix  <prefix>]]  [-spreadDist  <distance>  [-firstSpreadDist
       <distance>]]

       [-cell <cell1 cell2>]

       [-relativeDistToSink  <sinkWeight> | -offLoadAtLoc {x1a y1a x1b y1b x2a
       y2a x2b y2b ....} | { xLoc  yLoc  inv_xLoc  inv_yLoc}  |  -offLoadSlack
       <slack> | -spreadDist <distance> | -spreadCount <number> ]

       [-loc {xLoc yLoc} | { xLoc yLoc inv_xLoc inv_yLoc} | -noPlace ]

       Adds  either a single buffer or two inverters on a net. This allows you
       to optionally specify the location and radius, the location relative to
       the sink pin, and the buffer insertion based on the slack. This command
       also checks for and observes power domains based on the  specified  in-
       stance name and location. This command cuts wires by default.

       This  command does not modify dont_touch nets if setEcoMode -honorDont-
       Touch is set to true.

       Notes:

              * The ecoAddRepeater command is simultaneous setup/hold and MMMC
                aware. To make the command simultaneous setup/hold aware,  set
                the   global   variable   set_global  timing_enable_simultane-
                ous_setup_hold_mode to true. The simultaneous setup/hold  mode
                can  only  be  used for timing analysis. It cannot be used for
                any physical implementation steps.

                By default, if you specify an inverter  as  the  master  cell,
                ecoAddRepeater adds a pair of inverters but if you set setEco-
                Mode-LEQCheck  as false, ecoAddRepeater adds a single inverter
                only.

              * ecoAddRepeater can return new instance and net name:  newInst-
                Name inputNet outputNet

                Example

                set result [ecoAddRepeater -net s2_hresp0 -cell inv_32 \

                -loc {1069.018666 128.2435714}]

                set newInstName [lindex $result 0]

                set inputNetName [lindex $result 1]

                set outputNetName [lindex $result 2]

                If  a  pair of inverter is added then the return list could be
                the following, assuming inv1OutputNet drives the input pin  of
                inv2InstName:

                {inv1InstName  inv1InputNet inv1OutputNet inv2InstName inv2In-
                putNet inv2OutputNet}

              * When ecoAddRepeater is used in the post-mask ECO, ensure  that
                it  is  used  with  the  -noPlace  option  to avoid base layer
                change. Also, call ecoPlace -useSpareCells or ecoSwapSpareCell
                to map the new repeater to the spare cell. If you plan to call
                ecoRoute -modifyOnlyLayersbottomLayer:topLayer  later,  ensure
                that the added repeater can be connected through the specified
                layer.  Otherwise,  please  do not use the ecoAddRepeater com-
                mand. You can also use loadECO <ecofile> -postMask to add  re-
                peaters in the post-mask ECO.

Parameters
       -help  Outputs  a  brief description that includes the type and default
              information for each ecoAddRepeater.

              For a detailed description of the command and all of its parame-
              ters, use the man command:

              man ecoAddRepeater

       -bufOrient {R0 | R90 | R180 | R270 | MX | MX90 | MY | MY90}
              Specifies the legalized orientation for the instance.

              Valid orientation values are: R0, R90, R180, R270, MX, MX90, MY,
              MY90.

              Note: The -loc option is required with -bufOrient.

              For more information on orientation keys, see "Orientation  Key"
              in  the  Floorplanning  the  Design  chapter of the Innovus User
              Guide.

       -cell <cell1 cell2 ...>
              Specifies the name of the cell(s) which is to be inserted as re-
              peater.

       -firstSpreadDist <distance>
              Specifies the distance (from the driver) after which  the  first
              repeater  is  to be added. With the -firstSpreadDist option, you
              must specify -spreadDist.

              Minimum: 2.2250738585072e-308

              Maximum: 1073741.823

       -hinstGuide <hinstName>
              Indicates the module hierarchy in which the inst is inserted  by
              Tempus or a third party tool so that Innovus is able to make the
              association in case the instance appears in the -termList option
              of an ECO command at a later stage. This option can be only used
              when  setEcoMode  -batchMode true command is specified. You also
              need to specify the -name option along with it.

       -loc {x y | x1 y1 x2 y2}
              Specifies the x and y coordinates for the location of the buffer
              or inverter pair to insert. If no  location  is  specified,  the
              tool will automatically determine a location.

              * If  the  cell is a buffer and location is specified, the newly
                created buffer is placed at the specified location (x y).

              * If multiple buffers are added in the same ecoAddRepeater  com-
                mand,  the  buffers are added in the order of their locations,
                starting from the buffer farthest from the net's driver.

              * If the cell is an inverter pair and two locations  are  speci-
                fied,  the  first  inverter will be placed at location (x1 y1)
                and the second inverter will be placed at location (x2 y2).

              * If the cell is an inverter pair and only one location is spec-
                ified, both inverters will be placed at the same  location  (x
                y).

       -logicalChangeOnly
              Specifies  that  buffer/inverter  addition should be done in the
              logical-only mode.

       -name <instName>
              Specifies the base name for the repeater to be inserted.

              When -cell is inverter, you can specify two names  for  inverter
              pair enclosed in {{ }}.

       -net <netName  >
              Specifies the name of the net where the buffer will be inserted.

       -newNetName <netName>
              Specifies the base name for the new net created for the repeater
              insertion.

              When  -cell  is inverter, you can specify two names for inverter
              pair enclosed in {{ }}.

              ExampleecoAddRepeater -net DTMF_INST/ARB_INST/n_36  -cell  INVX4
              -name {{cell1 cell2}} -newNetName {{net1 net2}}

              Before

              After

       -noPlace
              Specifies that the inserted cells should not be placed. Only the
              logical change in connectivity will be made.

       -offLoadAtLoc {x1a y1a x1b y1b x2a y2a x2b y2b ....}
              Specifies  the  location(s)  at  which buffer (or inverter-pair)
              should be inserted to drive the sinks downstream from the  loca-
              tion(s).

       -offLoadSlack <slack>
              Inserts  a buffer to offload the paths with less than the speci-
              fied slack threshold from the driver  of  a  net  with  multiple
              cells. This option ignores the <term> option, if it is provided.
              This  option  is  used to connect the added buffer to drive only
              noncritical receivers, selected By Slack. This checks the timing
              graph for noncritical receivers  and  offloads  those  from  the
              critical  path, and could improve critical path timing by penal-
              izing noncritical path delays.

              Note:

              * The -offLoadAtLoc and -offLoadSlack options are  mutually  ex-
                clusive.

              * The -loc and -offLoadSlack options are mutually exclusive.

       -radius <mu>m
              Specifies  the  radius  in which the added instances are free to
              move. If no legal location can be found in the specified radius,
              the cells would be placed at the specified location resulting in
              an overlap with other cells. In that case,  you  should  perform
              legalization.

              Note: When the -radius option is used in ecoAddRepeater, {[-loc]
              [-relativeDistToSink] [-offLoadAtLoc]} must be specified.

       -relativeDistToSink <sinkWeight>
              Specifies  the location of the buffer based on its distance from
              the sink or the driver pin. The value is a number between 0  and
              1.  A  low  value  (0.1) places the buffer near the sink; a high
              value (0.9) places the buffer near the driver. The  fraction  is
              based on the length of the wire.

              This option works:

              * When one term is provided; it does not work if no term or mul-
                tiple terms are specified.

              * When -net with 1-sink net is provided. It does not work if the
                specified net is not a 1-sink net.

       -spreadCount <number>
              Specifies the number of repeaters to be added for buffering.

              Minimum: 1

              Maximum: INT_MAX

       -spreadDist <distance>
              Specifies  the  distance  (starting from the driver) after which
              repeaters are to be added.

              Minimum: 2.2250738585072e-308

              Maximum: 1073741.823

       -spreadPrefix <prefix>
              Specifies the prefix to be used for new instances and nets added
              during the spread buffering.

       -term <term1 term2>...
              Specifies a list of terms.  The  terms  specified  in  the  list
              should  be connected to a common net and the tool adds buffer to
              the common net. If -term is not specified, all the terms of  the
              net will be buffered.

       Note: You can specify the following in the setEcoMode command:

       setEcoMode -honorFixedStatus false #to modify FIXED instance.

       setEcoMode  -honorDontUse false #to modify instances which have dontUse
       attribute on cells.

       setEcoMode -honorDontTouch false #to  modify  instance/nets  which  are
       marked dontUse.

       setECOMode -honorFixedNetWire false #to insert a cell on wires with the
       FIXED/COVER   status   and  change  the  status  of  these  wires  from
       FIXED/COVER to ROUTED.

Examples
              *

                The following examples are the two methods to add two back-to-
                back inverters:

                *

                  The following example adds two instances  of  INV0  inverter
                  cell:

                  setEcoMode -LEQCheck true ; # default.

                  ecoAddRepeater -cell {INV0} -name {{inst_0 inst_1}} ...

                *

                  The  following  example adds two instances, one each of INV0
                  and INV1 inverter cells: -

                  setEcoMode -LEQCheck false ; # default: true.

                  ecoAddRepeater -cell {INV0 INV1} -name {inst_0 inst_1} ...

                  After the first (1) method, you can run the  following  com-
                  mand  to  change one of the two inverter instances to a dif-
                  ferent inverter  cell:  -ecoChangeCell  -cell  {INV1}  -inst
                  {<full hierarchical name of inst_1>}

              * The following syntax shows multiple buffer insertion:

                ecoAddRepeater  {-net|-term}  [-relativeDistToSink 0|1]  -cell
                {cell1  cell2 cell3..} [-loc <loc1> <loc2> <loc3>..] [-bufOri-
                ent <orient1>  <orient2>  <orient3>]  [-name  <name1>  <name2>
                <name3>..] [-newNetName  <name1> <name2> <name3>...]

              * The following command adds a buffer near the receiver:

                ecoAddRepeater                                            -net
                DTMF_INST/TDSP_CORE_INST/MPY_32_INST/M16X16_INST/n_784   -cell
                BUFX4 -relativeDistToSink 0.1

              * The following command adds a buffer near the driver:

                ecoAddRepeater                                            -net
                DTMF_INST/TDSP_CORE_INST/MPY_32_INST/M16X16_INST/n_784   -cell
                BUFX4 -relativeDistToSink 0.9

              * The following command adds a buffer in a specified location

                ecoAddRepeater -net wire_I10 -loc {51.5 85.67} -cell BUFFX4

              * The following command adds a buffer by specifying the terminal
                list:

                ecoAddRepeater   -cell   INVX4   -term   {i1/i2/in1  i1/i2/in2
                i1/i2/in3}

              * The following command adds an inverter pair by specifying  the
                slack time:

                ecoAddRepeater -net wire1_B2 -cell INVX4 -offLoadSlack -0.1

              *

                The following command adds an inverter pair:

                ecoAddRepeater  -net  myNet -cell INVX4 -loc {123 450 145 480}
                -name {{cell1 cell2}} -newNetName {{net1 net2}}

              * The  following  command  adds  inverter  pairs  and   multiple
                buffers:

                ecoAddRepeater -cell {inv_1 inv_2} -offLoadAtLoc  {x1a y1a x1b
                y1b x2a y2a x2b y2b}

                In the above example, {x1a y1a } {x1b y1b} buffers are for in-
                verter  pair 1 (inv_1) and {x2a y2a} {x2b y2b} buffers are for
                inverter pair2 (inv_2).

